s how the realist imagining of possessed bodies helped construct and naturalize racial difference, while excavating the complex, shifting, and dynamic possibilities embedded in ecstatic performance: its production of new and immanent forms of being beside. Across her readings of Stephen Crane, James Weldon Johnson, and Nella Larsen, among others, Reckson triangulates secularism, realism, and racial formation in the post-Reconstruction moment. Realist Ecstasy shows how post-Reconstruction realist texts mobilized gestures-especially the gestures associated with religious ecstasy-to racialize secularism itself. Reckson offers us a distinctly new vision of American realism as a performative practice, a sustained account of how performance lives in and through literary archives, and a rich sense of how closely secularization and racialization were linked in Jim Crow America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aPerformance in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aRealism in literature. 0aReligion in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAnna Julia Cooper.  aFrances E. W. Harper.  aGhost Dance.  aHamlin Garland.  aJames Mooney.  aJames Weldon Johnson.  aJim Crow.  aNella Larsen.  aPentecostalism.  aReconstruction.  aW. E. B. Du Bois.  aWilliam Dean Howells.  aWilliam Van der Weyde.  aaffect.  abody.  acapital punishment.  aconversion.  aelectricity.  aethnography.  agesture.  ahaunting.  aintersectionality.  alynching.  amessiah craze.  aperformance.  aphotography.  aqueerness.  arealism.  arecording.  areenactment.  asecularism.  asecularization.  asettler colonialism.  asexuality.  astorefront church.  atemporality.  awhiteness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dD